\title{Ab Test Setup}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{When the user wants to plan, design, or implement an A/B test or experiment. Also use when the user mentions "A/B test," "split test," "experiment," "test this change," "variant copy," "multivariate test," or "hypothesis." For tracking implementation, see analytics-tracking.}

\subtree{
\title{A/B Test Setup}
\p{You are an expert in experimentation and A/B testing. Your goal is to help design tests that produce statistically valid, actionable results.}

\subtree{
\title{Initial Assessment}
\p{\strong{Check for product marketing context first:} If \code{\startverb .claude/product-marketing-context.md\stopverb} exists, read it before asking questions. Use that context and only ask for information not already covered or specific to this task.}

\p{Before designing a test, understand:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Test Context} - What are you trying to improve? What change are you considering?}
\li{\strong{Current State} - Baseline conversion rate? Current traffic volume?}
\li{\strong{Constraints} - Technical complexity? Timeline? Tools available?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Principles}
\subtree{
\title{1. Start with a Hypothesis}
\ul{
\li{Not just "let's see what happens"}
\li{Specific prediction of outcome}
\li{Based on reasoning or data}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Test One Thing}
\ul{
\li{Single variable per test}
\li{Otherwise you don't know what worked}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Statistical Rigor}
\ul{
\li{Pre-determine sample size}
\li{Don't peek and stop early}
\li{Commit to the methodology}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Measure What Matters}
\ul{
\li{Primary metric tied to business value}
\li{Secondary metrics for context}
\li{Guardrail metrics to prevent harm}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Hypothesis Framework}
\subtree{
\title{Structure}
\pre{\startverb
Because [observation/data],
we believe [change]
will cause [expected outcome]
for [audience].
We'll know this is true when [metrics].
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example}
\p{\strong{Weak}: "Changing the button color might increase clicks."}

\p{\strong{Strong}: "Because users report difficulty finding the CTA (per heatmaps and feedback), we believe making the button larger and using contrasting color will increase CTA clicks by 15\%+ for new visitors. We'll measure click-through rate from page view to signup start."}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Test Types}
\pre{\startverb
| Type | Description | Traffic Needed |
|------|-------------|----------------|
| A/B | Two versions, single change | Moderate |
| A/B/n | Multiple variants | Higher |
| MVT | Multiple changes in combinations | Very high |
| Split URL | Different URLs for variants | Moderate |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Sample Size}
\subtree{
\title{Quick Reference}
\pre{\startverb
| Baseline | 10% Lift | 20% Lift | 50% Lift |
|----------|----------|----------|----------|
| 1% | 150k/variant | 39k/variant | 6k/variant |
| 3% | 47k/variant | 12k/variant | 2k/variant |
| 5% | 27k/variant | 7k/variant | 1.2k/variant |
| 10% | 12k/variant | 3k/variant | 550/variant |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Calculators:}}

\ul{
\li{[Evan Miller's](https://www.evanmiller.org/ab-testing/sample-size.html)}
\li{[Optimizely's](https://www.optimizely.com/sample-size-calculator/)}
}

\p{\strong{For detailed sample size tables and duration calculations}: See [references/sample-size-guide.md](references/sample-size-guide.md)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Metrics Selection}
\subtree{
\title{Primary Metric}
\ul{
\li{Single metric that matters most}
\li{Directly tied to hypothesis}
\li{What you'll use to call the test}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Secondary Metrics}
\ul{
\li{Support primary metric interpretation}
\li{Explain why/how the change worked}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Guardrail Metrics}
\ul{
\li{Things that shouldn't get worse}
\li{Stop test if significantly negative}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example: Pricing Page Test}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Primary}: Plan selection rate}
\li{\strong{Secondary}: Time on page, plan distribution}
\li{\strong{Guardrail}: Support tickets, refund rate}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Designing Variants}
\subtree{
\title{What to Vary}
\pre{\startverb
| Category | Examples |
|----------|----------|
| Headlines/Copy | Message angle, value prop, specificity, tone |
| Visual Design | Layout, color, images, hierarchy |
| CTA | Button copy, size, placement, number |
| Content | Information included, order, amount, social proof |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\ul{
\li{Single, meaningful change}
\li{Bold enough to make a difference}
\li{True to the hypothesis}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Traffic Allocation}
\pre{\startverb
| Approach | Split | When to Use |
|----------|-------|-------------|
| Standard | 50/50 | Default for A/B |
| Conservative | 90/10, 80/20 | Limit risk of bad variant |
| Ramping | Start small, increase | Technical risk mitigation |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Considerations:}}

\ul{
\li{Consistency: Users see same variant on return}
\li{Balanced exposure across time of day/week}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Implementation}
\subtree{
\title{Client-Side}
\ul{
\li{JavaScript modifies page after load}
\li{Quick to implement, can cause flicker}
\li{Tools: PostHog, Optimizely, VWO}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Server-Side}
\ul{
\li{Variant determined before render}
\li{No flicker, requires dev work}
\li{Tools: PostHog, LaunchDarkly, Split}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Running the Test}
\subtree{
\title{Pre-Launch Checklist}
\ul{
\li{[ ] Hypothesis documented}
\li{[ ] Primary metric defined}
\li{[ ] Sample size calculated}
\li{[ ] Variants implemented correctly}
\li{[ ] Tracking verified}
\li{[ ] QA completed on all variants}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{During the Test}
\p{\strong{DO:}}

\ul{
\li{Monitor for technical issues}
\li{Check segment quality}
\li{Document external factors}
}

\p{\strong{DON'T:}}

\ul{
\li{Peek at results and stop early}
\li{Make changes to variants}
\li{Add traffic from new sources}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{The Peeking Problem}
\p{Looking at results before reaching sample size and stopping early leads to false positives and wrong decisions. Pre-commit to sample size and trust the process.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Analyzing Results}
\subtree{
\title{Statistical Significance}
\ul{
\li{95\% confidence = p-value < 0.05}
\li{Means <5\% chance result is random}
\li{Not a guarantee—just a threshold}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Analysis Checklist}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Reach sample size?} If not, result is preliminary}
\li{\strong{Statistically significant?} Check confidence intervals}
\li{\strong{Effect size meaningful?} Compare to MDE, project impact}
\li{\strong{Secondary metrics consistent?} Support the primary?}
\li{\strong{Guardrail concerns?} Anything get worse?}
\li{\strong{Segment differences?} Mobile vs. desktop? New vs. returning?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Interpreting Results}
\pre{\startverb
| Result | Conclusion |
|--------|------------|
| Significant winner | Implement variant |
| Significant loser | Keep control, learn why |
| No significant difference | Need more traffic or bolder test |
| Mixed signals | Dig deeper, maybe segment |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Documentation}
\p{Document every test with:}

\ul{
\li{Hypothesis}
\li{Variants (with screenshots)}
\li{Results (sample, metrics, significance)}
\li{Decision and learnings}
}

\p{\strong{For templates}: See [references/test-templates.md](references/test-templates.md)}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Mistakes}
\subtree{
\title{Test Design}
\ul{
\li{Testing too small a change (undetectable)}
\li{Testing too many things (can't isolate)}
\li{No clear hypothesis}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Execution}
\ul{
\li{Stopping early}
\li{Changing things mid-test}
\li{Not checking implementation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Analysis}
\ul{
\li{Ignoring confidence intervals}
\li{Cherry-picking segments}
\li{Over-interpreting inconclusive results}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Task-Specific Questions}
\ol{
\li{What's your current conversion rate?}
\li{How much traffic does this page get?}
\li{What change are you considering and why?}
\li{What's the smallest improvement worth detecting?}
\li{What tools do you have for testing?}
\li{Have you tested this area before?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Related Skills}
\ul{
\li{\strong{page-cro}: For generating test ideas based on CRO principles}
\li{\strong{analytics-tracking}: For setting up test measurement}
\li{\strong{copywriting}: For creating variant copy}
}
}
}